            <fr:addr>forest://forester/gerby</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>http://www.jonmsterling.com/foreign/forester/gerby.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Gerby">Gerby</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Reference</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="external">https://gerby-project.github.io/</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>If you have a LaTeX document which</html:p>
            <html:ul><html:li>is large (probably several hundreds of pages at least)</html:li>
  <html:li>is regularly updated</html:li>
  <html:li>needs to be externally referenced often</html:li></html:ul>
            <html:p>you will run into the problem that</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li>large PDFs are not easily navigable</html:li>
  <html:li>PDFs of any size are not very searchable</html:li>
  <html:li>the internal numbering changes often, making external references outdated</html:li></html:ol>
            <html:p>Gerby addresses these problems by providing an online tag-based view, instead of just having a big PDF. Gerby is tailored towards making large online textbooks and reference works more accessible.</html:p>
            <html:p>In case you were wondering, a gerbe is a kind of stack (in the mathematical sense), and the software was originally meant for the <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/foreign/forester/stacks-project.xml" title="The Stacks project" addr="forest://forester/stacks-project" type="local">Stacks project</fr:link>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
